{"title_page": "Islamic marriage contract", "text_new": "{{Refimprove|date=April 2010}}\n[[File:Islamicmarriagecontract.jpg|thumb|An 1874 Islamic marriage contract.]]\n[[File:Signing the Nikah.jpg|thumb|180px|A bride signing the ''nikah nama'' ([[marriage contract]]).]]\nAn '''Islamic marriage contract''' is a formal, binding contract considered an integral part of an [[Islamic marriage]], and outlines the rights and responsibilities of the groom and bride or other parties involved in marriage proceedings.\n\n== Witnessing ==\n\nIn [[Sunni]] Islam, a marriage contract must have at least two witnesses. Proper witnessing is critical to the validation of the marriage, also acting as a protection against suspicions of adulterous relationships.\n\nIn [[Shia]] Islam, witnesses to a marriage are deemed necessary, but in case are not available then the two parties may conduct the nikah between themselves.<ref name=\"al-islam\">[http://al-islam.org/organizations/aalimnetwork/msg00200.html Witnesses for Marriage] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20051110182956/http://al-islam.org/organizations/aalimnetwork/msg00200.html |date=2005-11-10 }}, 'Aalim Network QR</ref>  It is also believed that temporary marriage, or [[Nikah Mut'ah]] (a type of contract which had more relaxed requirements) was prohibited in Sunni Islam, the necessity of witnessing was introduced by Sunni caliphs, specifically [[Umar]], to ensure that no couples engaged in secret union.\n\n== Authorization ==\nMarriages are usually not held in mosques, (depending on the country and culture of both where the marriage happens and the parties involved) because typically men and women are separated during the ceremony and reception. Islam doesn't authorize any official clergy, so any Muslim who understands the Islamic tradition can be the official for the wedding. However, if a Muslim wedding is held in a mosque, then a [[marriage officiant]], known as ''[[qadi]]'', ''qazi'' or ''madhun'' ({{lang-ar|\u0645\u0623\u0630\u0648\u0646}}), may preside over the wedding.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=HtJA40KjygIC|title=Vows & Toasts: Hundreds of Ways to Say I Do & Here's to You!|date=2014-05-14|publisher=Sellers Publishing, Incorporated|isbn=9781416207153|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Type and content ==\n{{Fiqh |marital}}\n\nAmong the stipulations that can be included in the marriage contract include giving up, or demanding, certain responsibilities.<ref name=\"Ibn Qudamah \">al-Mughni of Ibn Qudamah Vol. 9, Page 483</ref>\n\nThe Quran says that men are the protectors and maintainers of women<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.islamawakened.com/quran/4/34/ |title=Quran 4:34   Translation  Yusuf Ali (Orig. 1938) |work=Islam Awakened|accessdate=21 April 2020}}</ref> and from the Hadith, a man in turn is \"entitled\" the \"right to enjoy\" the \"(woman's) private parts\" as a \"stipulation of the marriage contract\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sunnah.com/bukhari/67/86  |title=Sunnah Bukhari   |author  = [[Muhammad al-Bukhari ]]|date=|work=Sunnah.com|accessdate=21 April 2020}}</ref>  This sexual dynamic is further expanded in other hadiths.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://abuaminaelias.com/dailyhadithonline/2013/05/13/nikah-respond-husband-needs/  |title=Hadith on Marriage |author=Sunan al-Tirmidh\u012b 1160|work=abuaminaelias.com|accessdate=21 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://sunnah.com/bukhari/67/128  |title=Wedlock, Marriage (Nikaah)|author=[[Sahih al-Bukhari|Bukhari]]|work=sunnah.com|accessdate=21 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://muflihun.com/ibnmajah/9/1853  |title=Book of Marriage Hadith 1853 |author= Sunan Ibn Majah|work=muflihun.com|accessdate=21 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nElaine Stokey writing in ''Scars Across Humanity: Understanding And Overcoming Violence Against Women'', says \"both the Quran and Hadiths contain passages which present women as the sexual property of men\".<ref name=\"Stokey\">{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com.au/books/about/Scars_Across_Humanity.html?id=WMRlCwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&source=kp_read_button&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q&f=false  |title=Scars Across Humanity: Understanding And Overcoming Violence Against Women |author=Stokey, Elaine|date=2015|accessdate=21 April 2020}}</ref> Nikki Keddie writing in ''Women in Middle Eastern History: Shifting Boundaries in Sex and Gender'' says, \"In all schools marriage is a contract, not a sacrament, and the man must provide materially for the wife and perform sexually.  The wife must have sex whenever the husband wishes, but she has no material obligations\".<ref name = \"Keddie\">{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?hl=en&lr=&id=FoS-xz192Z4C&oi=fnd&pg=PP2&dq=Women+in+Middle+Eastern+History:+Shifting+Boundaries+in+Sex+and+Gender&ots=ufsfpZ4N2x&sig=ASE5RutBT0Q5SYPkOtEhvujIneU#v=onepage&q=Women%20in%20Middle%20Eastern%20History%3A%20Shifting%20Boundaries%20in%20Sex%20and%20Gender&f=false |title=Women in Middle Eastern History: Shifting Boundaries in Sex and Gender |author=Keddie, Nikki|date=1992|work=[[Yale University Press]]| p=8|accessdate=21 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe marriage contract can also specify where the couple will live, whether or not the first wife will allow the husband to take a subsequent wife without her consent. The wife has the right to initiate divorce, it is called khula. She either gives back the dowry (mahr) or does not, depending on the reason for divorce. The man has the right to divorce. The marriage contract somewhat resembles the marriage settlements once negotiated for upper-class Western brides, but can extend to non-financial matters usually ignored by marriage settlements or [[pre-nuptial agreement]]s.\n\n== Purposes ==\n\nOne important purpose of the contract is to make sexual intercourse [[Fiqh|legal]]. This is supported by various [[Hadith]]s and quotations:\n\n[[Sahih Bukhari]], Book 62, #81:<ref name=\"bukhari\">[http://www.usc.edu/dept/MSA/fundamentals/hadithsunnah/bukhari/062.sbt.html#007.062.081 Sahih Bukhari, Book 62, #81] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070614011220/http://www.usc.edu/dept/MSA/fundamentals/hadithsunnah/bukhari/062.sbt.html#007.062.086 |date=2007-06-14 }}</ref>\n* ''Narrated 'Uqba: The [[Muhammad|Prophet]] ([[Peace be upon him|peace and blessings of Allah be upon him]]) said: \"The stipulations [in the marriage contract] most entitled to be abided by are those with which you are given the right to enjoy the (women's) private parts.\"''\n\nAl-Mughni (by Ibn Qudaamah), Kitab al Nikah:<ref name=\"mughni\">[http://muttaqun.com/marriage.html Marriage: According to the Qur'an and Sunnah] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120214071901/http://muttaqun.com/marriage.html |date=2012-02-14 }}, Muttaqun.com</ref>\n* ''... the Prophet (peace and blessings of Allah be upon him) [said]: \"The most deserving of conditions to be fulfilled are those by means of which sexual intercourse becomes permissible for you.\"''\n\nCited in (Al Aqad,2014) the common problem of translation of marriage contracts is due to the varieties of word synonyms in the legal Arabic system which have no equivalence in the English system in terms of marriage contracts, such as; \u0645\u0647\u0632\u064d, \u0634\u0628\u0643\u0647, \u0635\u062f\u0627\u0642. \u0627\u0644\u062e , Mahr, Shabkah, Sadaq- (dowry), whereas, all of these examples attributed and affected by the culture and tradition of the Arabic language.<ref name=\"al Aqad\">{{Cite journal|last=Al Aqad|first=Mohammed H.|date=2014|title=Translation of Legal Texts between Arabic and English: The Case Study of Marriage Contracts|url=http://www.awej.org/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=487:mohammed-h-al-aqad&catid=49&Itemid=152|journal=Arab World English Journal|volume=5|issue=2|pages=110\u2013121|via=}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Beena marriage]], a pre-Islamic form of marriage.\n*[[Islamic view of marriage]].\n*[[Islamic marital jurisprudence]].\n*[[Islamic marital practices]].\n*[[Islamic sexual jurisprudence]].\n*[[Islamic_views_on_slavery#Concubinage|Islamic views on slavery and concubinage]].\n*[[Islamic_sexual_jurisprudence#Prostitution|Islamic views on prostitution]].\n*[[Mahr]], a mandatory payment, paid or promised to be paid by the groom or his father to the bride at the time of marriage.\n*[[Marriage in Islam]]\n*[[Minangkabau marriage]], marriage practices of West Sumatra, Indonesia.\n*[[Nikah Halala]], the marriage of a woman to a second man after a triple talaq (divorce).\n*[[Nikah Ijtimah]], a pre-Islamic form of marriage.\n*[[Nikah Misyar]], a marriage practice in Sunni Islam.\n*[[Nikah mut\u2018ah]], a form of temporary marriage in Shia Islam, also known as sigeh or sigheh in Iran.\n*[[Nikah 'urfi]], a \"customary\" Sunni Muslim marriage contract.\n*[[Rights and obligations of spouses in Islam]].\n*[[Women in Islam]].\n*[[Divorce in Islam]].\n*[[Ketubah]], the Jewish marriage contract.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.muslimwedding.org/yartix.html Articles / Knowledge on Marriage within Islam] at muslimwedding.org\n\n\n[[Category:Islamic jurisprudence]]\n[[Category:Prenuptial agreements]]\n", "text_old": "{{Refimprove|date=April 2010}}\n[[File:Islamicmarriagecontract.jpg|thumb|An 1874 Islamic marriage contract.]]\n[[File:Signing the Nikah.jpg|thumb|180px|A bride signing the ''nikah nama'' ([[marriage contract]]).]]\nAn '''Islamic marriage contract''' is a formal, binding contract considered an integral part of an [[Islamic marriage]], and outlines the rights and responsibilities of the groom and bride or other parties involved in marriage proceedings.\n\n== Witnessing ==\n\nIn [[Sunni]] Islam, a marriage contract must have at least two witnesses. Proper witnessing is critical to the validation of the marriage, also acting as a protection against suspicions of adulterous relationships.\n\nIn [[Shia]] Islam, witnesses to a marriage are deemed necessary, but in case are not ava